06590nam a22009735i 9780812206920DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112010pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979741194  a97808122069207 a10.9783/97808122069202doi  a(DE-B1597)449484  a(OCoLC)794700706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a306.74/2089957051952221 aCheng, Sealing, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn the Move for Love :bMigrant Entertainers and the U.S. Military in South Korea /cSealing Cheng. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Angel Club -- tPart I. Setting the Stage -- t1. Sexing the Globe -- tPart II. Laborers of Love -- tVignette I. A Gijichon Tour in 2000 -- t2. ‘‘Foreign’’ and ‘‘Fallen’’ in South Korea -- t3. Women Who Hope -- tPart III. Transnational Women from Below -- tVignette II. A Day in Gijichon, December 1999 -- t4. The Club Regime and Club-Girl Power -- t5. Love ‘‘between My Heart and My Head’’ -- tPart IV. Home Is Where One Is Not -- tVignette III. Disparate Paths: The Migrant Woman and the NGO -- t6. At Home in Exile -- t7. ‘‘Giving Value to the Voices’’ -- t8. Hop, Leap, and Swerve–or Hope in Motion -- tAppendices -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the Korean War, gijichon—U.S. military camp towns—have been fixtures in South Korea. The most popular entertainment venues in gijichon are clubs, attracting military clientele with duty-free alcohol, music, shows, and women entertainers. In the 1990s, South Korea's rapid economic advancement, combined with the stigma and low pay attached to this work, led to a shortage of Korean women willing to serve American soldiers. Club owners brought in cheap labor, predominantly from the Philippines and ex-Soviet states, to fill the vacancies left by Korean women. The increasing presence of foreign workers has precipitated new conversations about modernity, nationalism, ethnicity, and human rights in South Korea. International NGOs, feminists, and media reports have identified women migrant entertainers as "victims of sex trafficking," insisting that their plight is one of forced prostitution.Are women who travel to work in such clubs victims of trafficking, sex slaves, or simply migrant women? How do these women understand their own experiences? Is antitrafficking activism helpful in protecting them? In On the Move for Love, Sealing Cheng attempts to answer these questions by following the lives of migrant Filipina entertainers working in various gijichon clubs. Focusing on their aspirations for love and a better future, Cheng's ethnography illuminates the complex relationships these women form with their employers, customer-boyfriends, and families. She offers an insightful critique of antitrafficking discourses, pointing to the inadequacy of recognizing women only as victims and ignoring their agency and aspirations. Cheng analyzes the women's experience in South Korea in relation to their subsequent journeys to other countries, providing a diachronic look at the way migrant issues of work, sex, and love fit within the larger context of transnationalism, identity, and global hierarchies of inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aForeign workers, FilipinozKorea (South). 0aMilitary bases, AmericanxSocial aspectszKorea (South). 0aMilitary bases, AmericanxSocial aspects. 0aProstitutionzKorea (South). 0aWomen foreign workerszKorea (South). 0aWomenzPhilippines. 4aHuman Rights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAnthropology.  aAsian Studies.  aFolklore.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aLinguistics.  aMiddle Eastern Studies.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220692040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812206920423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812206920.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041361-8  Penn Press eBook Package Social Sciences  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK